[7] Cholera - Malaysia (Sabah)
Date: Thu 5 Apr 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Daily Express News [edited]
<http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news.cfm?NewsID=48845>

The Health Department recorded 66 cholera cases in Sabah, compared to
227 cases in 2006. The recent cholera outbreak detected 15 cases and
54 health carriers in Sandakan on January 2007, followed by 20 cases
and 16 carriers in Kudat, 25 cases in Pitas with 18 carriers, and 5
cases and 6 carriers in Kota Marudu (all in March 2007).
A 6-year-old Indonesian illegal immigrant who died on 18 Mar 2007, on
the way to the Pitas hospital, was the only fatality. The localities
involved were 8 kampungs in Sandakan, 16 in Kudat, 10 in Pitas, and 7
in Kota Marudu. [Kampung is a word in Malay and Indonesian language,
which means village. - Mod.LL]
According to State Health Director, Datuk Dr Rahimah Mohd Said, 35
cholera cases and 62 carriers were still being treated at the
hospitals of the 4 districts. They comprised 3 cases and 40 carriers
in Sandakan, Kudat with 11 cases and 11 carriers, Pitas with 18 cases
and 12 carriers, and Kota Marudu with 5 cases and 2 carriers.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
