[8] Dysentery, diarrhea, post-disaster - Solomon Islands
Date: Fri 6 Apr 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: CNN International [edited]
<http://www.cnn.com/2007/WORLD/asiapcf/04/06/sopacific.quake.ap/>

The UN said Monday's (2 Apr 2007) earthquake/tsunami disaster killed
at least 34 people, though the Solomons' official toll is 28.
Government officials say they expect more deaths to be confirmed
later.
Susie Chippendale, communications manager for international Red Cross
operations in Gizo, said Fri 6 Apr 2007, that some dysentery cases
have been reported among those displaced by the disaster. "It seems
pretty under control at this stage, and hopefully there won't be a
huge outbreak," she said.
Unhygienic conditions and a lack of clean water have contributed to
diarrhea outbreaks in several of the makeshift camps where at least
2000 survivors are staying near Gizo.
Dr. Gregory Jilini, the senior health official in Western Province,
said work has begun to build pit toilets in the camps to fend off
disease.
Officials fear malaria and cholera could break out in hillside camps,
where thousands of people who fled are afraid to leave, fearing
another wave.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
